[audience laughs]
Thank you. I got it.

00:37:03.289 --> 00:37:08.060
&gt;&gt;Female Audience Member #2: So did they give
you a grant to start this or did you finish

00:37:08.060 --> 00:37:09.989
the book and go to them? Or how,..
&gt;&gt;Brenda Marshall: It actually backs up a

00:37:09.989 --> 00:37:16.380
little bit because my first novel had been
published by a mainstream New York press.

00:37:16.380 --> 00:37:22.089
My hope of course was to go back to them because
that's where most of the marketing will be

00:37:22.089 --> 00:37:27.039
available. And, but my agent went, my agent
was the -- first you have to have an agent.

00:37:27.039 --> 00:37:29.869
You have to have a literary agent
&gt;&gt;Female Audience Member #2: Right.

00:37:29.869 --> 00:37:34.109
&gt;&gt;Brenda Marshall: in New York. And for this
type of book, but my agent wasn't able to

00:37:34.109 --> 00:37:38.530
sell it to one of the New York houses. And
I kept getting this thing over and over again,

00:37:38.530 --> 00:37:42.109
which was: 'Love the story. Great writing.
Great characters. We've never read this story

00:37:42.109 --> 00:37:46.319
before but we don't know how we would market
it to a wide audience.'

00:37:46.319 --> 00:37:51.210
Because they, they have jobs to keep and they
have, -- it all has a lot to do with selling

00:37:51.210 --> 00:37:57.690
books which in some ways that's too bad because
there are a lot of really great books that

00:37:57.690 --> 00:38:01.549
aren't making it into that best seller range.
Anyway so then I said to my agent, 'Let's

00:38:01.549 --> 00:38:09.789
try University Presses because there is a,
it is [pause] honest historical fiction and

00:38:09.789 --> 00:38:14.420
it is literary historical fiction. So I think
the University Presses would work.'

00:38:14.420 --> 00:38:19.280
I actually went to undergraduate school in
North Dakota State University. So my agent

00:38:19.280 --> 00:38:24.869
was able to talk to the people back there
and I was able to talk to them and they were

00:38:24.869 --> 00:38:29.650
thrilled. They have actually been thrilled
to publish this book and have done just a

00:38:29.650 --> 00:38:33.759
gorgeous job with it. And there's actually
something kind of positive about not having

00:38:33.759 --> 00:38:38.660
a mainstream New York house which I would
have not have complained about.

00:38:38.660 --> 00:38:46.630
Don't get me wrong. But with, -- if a book
is published, say by Random House or Knopf

00:38:46.630 --> 00:38:53.000
for something big and splashy, it doesn't
have much time to make it on the bookshelf.

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:58.500
And we all know the bookshelves are sort of
disappearing. And so you, -- the, -- there's

00:38:58.500 --> 00:39:05.079
a sense that you make it right away or you
don't. But the joy of having a University

00:39:05.079 --> 00:39:09.489
Press to do this is that they're in it for
the long haul. And so there can be this sort

00:39:09.489 --> 00:39:12.599
of grass roots understanding that there is
a good book out there and word of mouth still

00:39:12.599 --> 00:39:16.359
does sell books and still does get enthusiasm
going.

00:39:16.359 --> 00:39:25.599
But also I'm lucky in that I have an e-publisher
and so people who do not have access to -- it's

00:39:25.599 --> 00:39:33.752
available on Amazon dot com too. But who don't
want to buy a hardback can get it on any e-reader

00:39:33.752 --> 00:39:35.779
which is a useful thing these days when book
stores are sort of disappearing.

00:39:35.779 --> 00:39:36.779
[pause]
Anything else?

00:39:36.779 --> 00:39:39.579
&gt;&gt;Female Audience Member #3: So who do you
feel like were your biggest mentors or are

00:39:39.579 --> 00:39:46.809
your mentors in the industry?
&gt;&gt;Brenda Marshall: I don't know that I actually

00:39:46.809 --> 00:39:53.969
have mentors in the industry. I have people
who have been very, very good to me and helpful.

00:39:53.969 --> 00:40:02.700
I am one of these writers who does not really
like to share work while I'm writing. I want

00:40:02.700 --> 00:40:09.489
to be as done as I can get before I actually
show somebody. And then a process of revision

00:40:09.489 --> 00:40:14.119
always happens. The agent says, 'Well'.
My agent, when she first read my book which

00:40:14.119 --> 00:40:18.170
is 200 pages longer, she said, 'You have two
wonderful books here. You have a history book

00:40:18.170 --> 00:40:20.900
and a novel. [audience laughs] Which one would
you like to publish?'

00:40:20.900 --> 00:40:24.819
So then it comes back to me and I have to
get rid of 200 pages which was probably a

00:40:24.819 --> 00:40:34.059
good thing to do. Broke my heart but I did
it. And again it was a good thing to do. So

00:40:34.059 --> 00:40:39.369
then there's that sort of revising going on
and editors will ask for revisings.

00:40:39.369 --> 00:40:46.469
But for the most part, I want to -- it's not
so much that I only trust myself. It's that

00:40:46.469 --> 00:40:51.810
I don't trust that I won't take advice that
isn't good. I really trust readers when they

00:40:51.810 --> 00:40:55.039
talk to me and they say, 'Well this didn't
work. This didn't work. This could have been

00:40:55.039 --> 00:40:56.039
better.'
And I think, 'Okay. I have to change this.

00:40:56.039 --> 00:40:57.900
I have to change that. I have to make this
better.''

00:40:57.900 --> 00:41:03.430
And then a part of me thinks, 'Is that true
to the book itself, to the heart of the book

00:41:03.430 --> 00:41:07.210
itself?'
And so that's why I work mostly on my own.

00:41:07.210 --> 00:41:15.319
But there are people saying, people at the
University of Michigan. Peter Ho Davies has

00:41:15.319 --> 00:41:22.479
been, was good enough to write this lovely
blurb on the background, on the back, comparing

00:41:22.479 --> 00:41:25.229
my book to George Eliot's 'Middlemarch'. Not.
[audience laughter]

00:41:25.229 --> 00:41:34.329
I just want to say that that is, that is the
most wonderful thing that anybody could say.

00:41:34.329 --> 00:41:38.460
I know who George Eliot is. I know. I know
how far to take that comparison. But what

00:41:38.460 --> 00:41:45.079
he's talking, what he is saying is that there's
this big panoramic background and , or also

00:41:45.079 --> 00:41:49.890
comparing it to Sarah Waters' fiction which
if you are readers of Sarah Waters, she writes

00:41:49.890 --> 00:41:55.661
really terrific historical fiction.
Charlie Baxter used to teach here at the University

00:41:55.661 --> 00:42:00.219
of Michigan. He's now at the University of
Minnesota. And his book, 'Feast of Love',

00:42:00.219 --> 00:42:06.400
was a National Book Award finalist. And he
has been a good help to me throughout too.

00:42:06.400 --> 00:42:10.089
In terms of actually -- those are the people
who help you once you've written the book

00:42:10.089 --> 00:42:18.550
and are saying, 'Okay. I want to help this
see a public.' In terms of writers that have

00:42:18.550 --> 00:42:24.900
been meaningful to me, I think I am more inclined
to talk about books that have been meaningful

00:42:24.900 --> 00:42:30.029
as opposed to writers 'cause I often don't
follow one writer's work down the line.

00:42:30.029 --> 00:42:37.710
I'll think after awhile and Salman Rushdie
is a terrific author whose first four books

00:42:37.710 --> 00:42:41.849
I just could not read fast enough. And I don't
know if I'll read any more of his books. You

00:42:41.849 --> 00:42:45.109
know you get to a point where you don't know
if you'll read any more.

00:42:45.109 --> 00:42:50.849
'The Great Gatsby'. Jay Gatsby who was originally
James Gadson, -- I don't know if any of you

00:42:50.849 --> 00:42:54.819
remember that, -- from North Dakota. That's
part of his, that's part of his story and

00:42:54.819 --> 00:42:59.229
part of that drive. That belief that you can
do anything if just you work hard enough even

00:42:59.229 --> 00:43:02.049
if what you want might not be such a good
thing. Or your drive.

00:43:02.049 --> 00:43:05.799
The way you get what you want might not be
so good but that sense of 'ok, iIf I just

00:43:05.799 --> 00:43:11.559
follow the rules, if I just fill in these
squares, I can succeed.' And that's a very

00:43:11.559 --> 00:43:17.130
Midwestern, very North Dakota way of thinking.
So that book has been crucial to me.

00:43:17.130 --> 00:43:21.390
'Middlemarch' again has been crucial just
in terms of watching

00:43:21.390 --> 00:43:29.220
[pause]
George Eliot's intelligence work at work in

00:43:29.220 --> 00:43:38.180
a novel. Just that, the bravery of watching
that much intelligence in the midst of a really

00:43:38.180 --> 00:43:45.769
compelling story and of being able to devise
a world that was so huge, all at once. That

00:43:45.769 --> 00:43:50.660
was, that was, that was pretty meaningful
to me. She's somebody's books I read over

00:43:50.660 --> 00:43:56.440
and over and over again.
If anybody here has never read anything by

00:43:56.440 --> 00:44:02.569
Marilyn Robinson, 'Housekeeping' is my favorite.
But she has others. That's a book, those are

00:44:02.569 --> 00:44:07.960
books to run out and get. And again, she has
been an influence I would say in the sense

00:44:07.960 --> 00:44:15.180
again of what quiet intelligence can do and
how much you can just fall in love with certain

00:44:15.180 --> 00:44:20.339
characters. It is just her –' Housekeeping
' is just a small book but it is, it is, it

00:44:20.339 --> 00:44:23.420
is so beautifully written.
I mean, I'm dobeing this advertisement for

00:44:23.420 --> 00:44:24.420
'Housekeeping'.
[audience laughter[

00:44:24.420 --> 00:44:28.700
It is so beautifully written that it almost
scans like poetry and yet it is smart and

00:44:28.700 --> 00:44:36.400
it is funny and it is just, -- it is just
the book I think everybody ought to be reading.

00:44:36.400 --> 00:44:37.769
[pause]
Anything else?

00:44:37.769 --> 00:44:40.049
[pause]
All right. Thank you.

00:44:40.049 --> 00:44:45.289
Male Audience Member #2: Thank you so much.
This has been great.

00:44:45.289 --> 00:44:45.799
[applause]

